radiographic_examinations.findings: No evidence of acute aortic syndrome. The thoracic aorta is normal in caliber throughout. No dissection, penetrating ulcer, intramural hematoma, or other aortic abnormality. The great vessels have normal origins and are normal in the visualized portions beyond the origins of the vertebral arteries for the subclavians and into the base of the neck for the carotid arteries. The descending thoracic aorta is normal in appearance and the major arterial branches in the upper abdomen. Bilateral renal arteries are normal in appearance. No significant atherosclerosis noted. No evidence for pulmonary embolism within the central pulmonary arteries. No other mediastinal or thoracic abnormality evident. Heart size is within normal limits. No abnormality is evident in the visualized portions of the upper abdomen.
